3}{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
 Constraint Satisfaction Problems form a class of computational decision problems of the following form. We fix a relational structure A (think of a graph, or a digraph, or a partial order) that we call the template and consider}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
the CSP of A, which is the following problem: on an input B, which is finite, we ask whether there is a homomorphism from B to A.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
Instanciating A with particular structures, we obtain some well-known problems.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
Perhaps one of the most famous problems is the problem of determining whether a finite graph admits a proper coloring with k colors, where k is a fixed number.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
A coloring is a function from the vertices of the graph to k colors that maps adjacent vertices to different colors. Another way of saying this is that a coloring is a homomorphism from the graph to the complete graph on k vertices, i.e., CSP(K_k) is precisely the k-coloring problem.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
A second example is the problem of determining whether a finite digraph is free of directed cycles. This is equivalent to asking whether the vertices can be numbered in a way that if there is an arc from u to v, then the number of u is less than the number of v. In other words, we are asking for a homomorphism to (Q;<). We could choose here any infinite linear order, but one can show that it is not possible to choose a finite structure A doing the job. In other words, the class of arbitrary CSPs is a proper superclass of finite-domain CSPs.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
Finally, the problem of feasibility of systems of diophantine equations asks for an assignment of the variables to integer numbers in a way that a system of polynomial constraints are satisfied. Up to some coding of the input, this is asking for a homomorphism to the structure (Z;+,x,1) where + and x are seen as ternary relations.}
