\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs60\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs60\loch\f5
4 }{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
Complexity theory is the theory of resources that are needed to answer questions. The relevant definitions for this talk are the following. P is the class of decision problems for which there exists a deterministic algorithm whose worst-case running time is bounded by a polynomial in the size of the input. NP is the class of problems for which there exists an algorithm running in polynomial time, where the algorithm is allowed to make guesses. We call NP-hard any problem that is at least as hard as any problem in NP.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
P is a subset of NP by definition, but the converse is not known to hold. It could a priori be the case that NP splits into two subclasses: P and the NP-hard problems (we call this a dichotomy). However, Ladner proved that this is not the case: either P=NP, or there are problems in NP that are neither in P nor NP-hard, i.e., they are \u8220\'93in the middle\u8221\'94. Ladner\u8217\'92s theorem relies on a diagonalization method: one enumerates the polynomial-time deterministic algorithms and all the possible proofs of NP-hardness. Both of these sets are countable, and one constructs a decision problem that avoids these two sets.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
In their semina}{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
l}{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
 paper on CSPs, Feder and Vardi got the intuition that although finite-domain CSPs are very expressive, on cannot reproduce this diagonalization method and produce an NP-intermediate problem that would be a finite-domain CSP. The intuition was supported at the time by Schaefer\u8217\'92s theorem, who proved that 2-element CSPs exhibit a dichotomy, and the theorem by Hell and Nesetril achieving the same result for the CSPs of finite undirected graphs.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
The intuition of Feder and Vardi was proven to be right last year. Bulatov and Zhuk, indepently, proved that finite-domain CSPs are in P or NP-hard. I want to attract your attention on the following fact: determining the complexity of a single problem can be tricky. Bulatov and Zhuk here determined the complexity of infinitely many problems. How?}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs60\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs60\loch\f5
5}{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
 Instead of focussing on how the complexity of a CSP changes with the template, it is useful to consider what constructions leave the complexity invariant. It was observed by Jeavons and coauthors that adding relations to a template does not increase the complexity of the corresponding CSP, provided that this new relation can be defined in a weak fragment of first-order logic that we call \u8220\'93primitive positive\u8221\'94, and which consists of the first-order formulas that only use existential quantifications and conjunctions.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
For example, I claim that the CSP of the 5-cycle C_5 is NP-hard. To prove this, look at the binary relation that holds for pairs (x,y) that are connected by a path of length 3 in C_5. This relation is clearly definable in the primitive positive fragment, and indeed here is a definition. This relation is actually the full irreflexive relation, i.e., it is the graph K_5 whose CSP is well-known to be NP-hard.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
What this observation implies is that by closing A under primitive positive definability, one obtains an invariant of the complexity of CSP(A). Such objects are called coclones (or relational clones) and have been studied for many years. In other words, the study of CSPs is nothing more than the study of coclones.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs60\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs60\loch\f5
6}{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
 Let\u8217\'92s now move to an overview of the results in my dissertation. At the top of the picture, one finds the class of all CSPs. This contains, up to technicalities, every decision problem. There is a natural way of dividing this class: on the left side, there is the class of CSPs whose template is omega-categorical, and on the right side there is the class of CSPs that can \u8220\'93count\u8221\'94, in some sense.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
Omega-categoricity is a model-theoretic notion that I will not define, for the reason that the class of interest in the first part of my dissertation is a proper subclass, that I will call the \u8220\'93Bodirsky-Pinsker\u8221\'94 or BP class in the rest of the talk. The BP class contains all finite structures and is a class of structures whose CSPs are all in NP. Bodirsky and Pinsker conjectured a complexity dichotomy for this class, similar to the then-conjectured dichotomy for finite-domain CSPs. In the first part of my dissertation, I present a general tractability result for the CSPs in this class, as well as proofs of the dichotomy conjecture for two natural subclasses that I call here Monotone Monadic SNP and reducts of unary structures. I will give a more detailed presentation of these results in the next part of my talk.}
