A structure is additionally called finitely bounded if one can characterize its age by forbidding finitely many substructures. All the examples that I gave are finitely bounded: for the case of the rational order, one forbids loops, unrelated vertices, and a cycle of length 3. For the Rado graph, one forbids loops and directed edges. For the Henson graph, one additionally forbids triangles. A finitely bounded homogeneous structure has the property that it can be described uniquely (up to isomorphism) by a finite amount of information: one specifies the forbidden substructures, this describes uniquely a class of finite structures which in turn described uniquely a homogeneous structure. This generalises to any structure whose relations are definable over a finitely bounded homogeneous structure, and in particular this implies that the CSP of any structure that is definable over a finitely bounded homogeneous structure is in NP.}
