8}{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
 Before stating the Bodirsky-Pinsker conjecture, let me introduce clones. In universal algebra, a clone is a set of operations of finite arity on a common set, containing all the projection operations, and being closed under composition. The clone that we consider here come from relational structures in the following way. Given a relational structure A, we consider the set of its polymorphisms, which are the functions that preserve every relation of A. The preservation condition is a simple generalisation of the preservation condition for endomorphisms of a structure, and I will not state it here. Polymorphisms are often considered as higher-order symmetries of the structure, generalising automorphisms and endomorphisms. It can be easily checked that the set Pol(A) of all polymorphisms of A forms a clone, that carries additionally a topological structure coming from the topology of pointwise convergence, the base set A being considered a discrete space. }
