10}{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
 One of the major tools that we have to approach this conjecture are so-called canonical functions. A function f is said to be canonical with respect to some background structure B if it induces a function on the orbits of B. Said differently, a function is canonical if locally, one can represent f composed with automorphisms of B as some automorphism of B composed with f. It can be checked that the subset of a clone C consisting of all the functions that are canonical with respect to the same background structure forms a subclone of C, that is, it contains the projection operations and is closed under composition. This subclone is called the canonical subclone of C.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5

\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
The interesting aspect of this is that if B is homogeneous in some language with bounded arity m, then there are only finitely many orbits of m-tuples, and a clone of canonical functions acts by definition on this finite set of orbits of m-tuples. One can then use this fact to try to lift results coming from the theory of finite clones and finite algebras. In particular, we were able to prove the following: for a Bodirsky-Pinsker structure A, if the canonical subclone of the polymorphisms of A does not have a homomorphism to the clone of projections, then the CSP of A is in P. One of the consequences is that the dichotomy conjecture holds for those structures whose polymorphisms are all canonical.}
