\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\alang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang2057\qj\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640{\cf1\afs28\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs28\loch\f5
Now, hoping that this problem has a positive solution is not only wishful thinking. Bodirsky, Pinsker, and Tsankov proved that if the background structure B satisfies some extra assumption, namely that of being Ramsey, then every function behaves canonically on arbitrarily large substructures of B. One can restate this by saying that every function has a \u8220\'93canonical friend\u8221\'94 that is in some way locally the same as the original function. This result was first proved in the context of Ramsey theory, and it was later reproved using the Kechris-Pestov-Todorcevic correspondence which says that B is Ramsey if and only if its automorphism group is extremely amenable. One can then define rather easily an action of Aut(B) on some compact Hausdorff space whose fixpoints correspond to canonical functions, and extreme amenability entails the existence of such fixpoints.}
